ME:
i'd like to make a logic simulation website where a user can draw circuits from NAND gates and *NO* other logic gates.  there are *no* flip flops, *no* AND gates, *no* OR gates, etc.
there are other features though:
wires are bidirectional and instant and have only 0 or 1 states, error if the user tries to connect two outputs.  connecting tristate outputs is allowed.  wire routing snaps to grid and allows multiple way points on the path and allows junctions between two wires.  when two wires connect, add a schematic dot to show the connect and don't just cross.
there is a RAM chip with tristate output and a selectable number of address pins. The RAM chip can load a basic binary file from a URL.  it has WE and EN pins, WE accepts data on the falling edge, EN controls the tristate output. allow a way of pulling updated binaries from the url on demand.
there is an 8 bit and a 1 bit input and output. (bit 0 is LSB and the schematic shows bit 0 at the top) 8 bit inputs and outputs show the value in decimal, hex, and binary, make sure they don't overlap.  each i/o bit can be named independently but defaults to an optional output name (default blank) followed by 0-7.  (i.e. Y0 to Y7 for an output named Y) each input can be set by double clicking any of the 3 numbers and setting the value in that radix.  inputs also have an up/down button to inc/dec the current value.  inputs and outputs also have a grid of LEDs that can be clicked to toggle them.
there is also a tristate primitive with it's data bit and enable if the output is on, otherwise it's tristated.
there is a "0" primitive that simply outputs a low/0/false.  
there is a clock that toggles at a user specified rate in hz, including values like 0.1hz.

circuits can be saved to make a new custom component (known as a "chip") which show up in the list with the original primitives on the bottom task bar.  chips can be edited and renamed.  any circuit that makes use of a renamed chip continues to use that chip, so you'll have to have an immutable internal id for each.  deleting a chip will however break anything using it, so warn if another circuit uses one before completing the delete of a saved chip.

the entire workspace and defined chips is a "project" and there has to be a way to export them (download local), import them (upload local), and pull one from a url via both a menu and an option in the url of the sim. (i serve via nginx, please provide instructions for the cross site issues when the time comes.)
there should be a menu item for showing the logic table for the current circuit workspace (it should be available in the chip editor as well)
when editing a chip, there should be an option to drop back out of the chip and return to the prior workspace.  i'm also open to the idea that chip edits are opened in tabs that can be closed when done editing and can save to the defined chip on demand. you tell me what is easier.

there should be a way to highlight primitives and chips on the workspace to mass delete as well as copy and paste.  any wires between copied chips should come with when pasted, wires to primitives chips not copy/pasted should not be included.

there should be a menu item for synthesizing a circuit from a user entered logic table, allow setting the number of inputs and outputs.  when synthesizing, reduce the boolean equation then first attempt to make use of custom chips before resorting to the NAND primitive.  the user will likely make things like AND, OR, NOT, XOR early on, but do not create these "chips" if the user has not created them themselves.  if the current workspace is not empty, prompt the user to add it to this space or save as a chip.

the simulation itself is edge mapped, a queue of connected changes is maintained and propagated through the circuit.  each NAND element has an output change counter which allows loop detection.  
a circuit such as not->not->not-> back to the original not should fail with a warning.  clocking is via a clock primitive, not simulated gate delays.  an s-r flip flop or d-flip flop are not errors, if there is a conflict in this statement, tell me don't just resolve it.

i prefer a dark theme with colors similar to falstad.com's circuitjs.

do not generate code yet.  please describe the entire project, break it into appropriate testable modules, identify tests as well as areas not able to be covered by tests.

i prefer functions that fit on a single screen, avoid large functions but also do not refactor without asking permission first.  every function must have a defined interface that does not change without asking permission.  edits must be as small as possible, treat this as a github project where someone has to do a review of every diff and doesn't want to see dozens of spacing changes or variable renames or comment edits and definitely doesn't want to see changes unrelated to the specific pull request.  if something you think needs doing requires permission, do not generate code but instead stop and ask.

