AI:
High-level summary

A single-page web app (TypeScript + React or Preact) with a canvas-based schematic editor and deterministic, event/edge-driven logic simulator restricted to NAND primitives plus a few primitives (RAM, tristate, clock, 0, I/O). Project is organized into composable, testable modules (UI, data model, simulator, persistence, chip manager, synthesis, networking). Below is a decomposition, data and API sketches, test plan, and a list of holes/conflicts/decision points you must resolve before implementation.
Core requirements (condensed)

    Only NAND as logic gate primitive (no built-in AND/OR/NOT etc.), but user can save chips that implement those.
    Wires are bidirectional, instantaneous, carry 0/1, error if two outputs directly connected (except tristate outputs allowed).
    Grid-snapped, multi-waypoint routing, junction dots when wires connect.
    RAM primitive: tri-state output, n address pins, WE (captures on falling edge), EN (controls tri-state), can load binary file from URL and re-pull on demand.
    Inputs/Outputs: 8-bit and 1-bit devices, show decimal/hex/binary (bit0 = top), editable by radix, up/down, clickable LED grid; per-bit names with default pattern.
    Tristate primitive (data + enable).
    "0" primitive outputs constant 0.
    Clock primitive with user-specified Hz (down to 0.1 Hz).
    Chips: user can save circuits as chips, edit/rename (immutable internal id), editing should preserve references, delete warns/blocks if used.
    Project: workspace + defined chips; export/import local file + load from URL (menu + URL param). Serve via nginx — provide cross-site instructions when asked.
    Logic table view for workspace and chip editor.
    Chip editing: option to return to parent workspace; tabs allowed — you prefer suggestion.
    Selection, mass-delete, copy/paste (preserve internal wires within selection; external wires to filtered-out primitives not included).
    Synthesis from logic table; prefer custom chips where available before NAND fallback; prompt when adding to non-empty workspace.
    Simulator: edge-mapped queue, propagate changes, per-NAND output change counter for loop detection; detect and warn on combinational loops (e.g., NOT->NOT->NOT cycle).
    UI: dark theme similar color palette to Falstad.
    Small functions, fixed interfaces, minimal edit diffs. Stop and ask before permission-required refactors.

Proposed architecture and modules

(Each module returns a clearly typed JS/TS interface. Keep functions small; expose only necessary API. Interfaces are immutable unless changed with explicit permission.)

    App shell / Router
        Responsibilities: global state container (project), top menu, chip editor tabs, project import/export, URL param loading, theme.
        Exposed APIs: loadProject(projectJson), saveProject(): ProjectJson, openChipEditor(chipId), closeChipEditor(chipId).
    Data model (pure immutable structures, e.g., Immutable.js or readonly TypeScript types)
        Types: Project, Workspace, Chip (id immutable UUID), PrimitiveInstance, Wire (ordered waypoint list), Net (computed connected net), Pins (typed: input/output/tristate/addr/WE/EN/clock).
        APIs: createPrimitive(spec), movePrimitive(id, x,y), createWire(points, fromPin,toPin), computeNets(workspace): Net[]
        Persistence: toJSON/fromJSON (stable schema versioned).
    Canvas & Editor
        Responsibilities: render grid, primitives, wires (junction dots), selection box, copy/paste, drag routing with multi-waypoints, snapping, keyboard handlers.
        APIs: renderWorkspace(workspace), startWire(fromPin), addWaypoint(x,y), finishWire(toPin), select(ids), copySelection(), pasteAt(x,y).
    Pin & Wiring rules engine
        Responsible for structural validation: detect invalid output-output connections (except tristate). When wiring endpoints change, produce user-visible error markers.
        API: validateConnection(pinA,pinB): {ok:boolean, reason?:string}.
    Net manager
        Builds nets from wires and pins (accounting for tristate; tristate driven nets treated specially). Exposes mapping pin -> netId and net state.
        API: computeNetGraph(workspace): {nets, pinToNet}
    Simulator / Event queue
        Edge-mapped propagation engine:
            Maintains current state for each pin and net.
            Events: (pinId, oldVal, newVal, timeTick, edge type)
            NAND primitive semantics implemented here (exposed as SimulationPrimitive interface).
            NAND output change counter per element to detect loops; counter threshold config; on exceed, stop and report a combinational loop.
            Clock primitive enqueues toggle events at configured intervals (Hz as floating value).
            WE semantics: falling-edge sampling (detect previous=1 & now=0).
            Tristate: if disabled, pin is high-impedance (Z); nets with only Z drivers are undefined -> treat as 0 by default? (decision point below).
        API: stepSimulation(dt), run(), pause(), injectInput(pinId,value), snapshot(), restore(snapshot).
    Primitive library (simulation + rendering)
        NAND, Tristate, 0-const, Clock, RAM, 1-bit I/O, 8-bit I/O.
        RAM implementation:
            Addr pins: configurable count N -> depth 2^N words (with size 8 bits? decision: default word width = 8 — clarify).
            WE: latch on falling edge, sample data bus on falling edge.
            EN: controls tristate output.
            Load from URL: fetch binary blob and map into words (endianness and word size decision needed).
            API: loadFromUrl(url), reload(), setMemoryAt(addr,bytes).
    Chip manager (save/load chips)
        Persist chips with immutable internal id; chips reference primitives and connections; editing a chip opens editor; renames change only metadata.
        Deletion warns about usage in workspace; delete only after confirm.
        API: createChip(workspaceSnapshot, name), renameChip(id,name), deleteChip(id), getChipUsage(chipId): WorkspaceLocations[].
    Synthesis engine (logic-table -> netlist)
        Input: truth table, input count, output count.
        Algorithm: minimize boolean expressions per-output (e.g., Quine–McCluskey or Espresso core) then attempt to map sub-expressions to existing chips (exact match on interface), otherwise synthesize into NAND network.
        If workspace is non-empty: prompt (add to current workspace vs save as chip).
        API: synthesize(truthTable, preferChips=true) -> ChipDefinition or WorkspaceAdditions.
    UI: I/O controls
        8-bit and 1-bit renderers: display decimal/hex/bin without overlap, bit0 at top, per-bit name, double-click editable per radix, up/down buttons, LED grid clickable toggles.
        API: onValueChange(callback), setValueFromRadix(value, radix).
    Serialization / Project import-export
        Export: single JSON (versioned), includes chips and workspace. Optionally gzip/base64 compress.
        Import: validate schema version; if external chips conflict (id collisions), reassign ids and optionally remap references.
        URL loading: accept URL param ?projectUrl=..., UI menu to fetch and load project.
        Provide CORS guidance separately (see decision list).
    Tests & harness
        Unit tests for pure modules: data model, net computation, validateConnection, simulator primitives, NAND semantics, RAM edge behavior, serialization.
        Integration tests: small circuits (in code) run through simulator step sequences to verify expected outputs.
        E2E tests (headless browser): UI interactions: wire routing, save/load, copy/paste.
        Performance tests: large net counts and propagation queue stress tests.
    Devops / build
        Static build served by nginx, SPA; service worker optional for offline.

