Areas difficult or impossible to fully cover with automated tests

    Visual layout / pixel-perfect rendering (dots, non-overlapping value boxes) — requires manual or visual-diff tests.
    User experience flows (usability of route editing, multi-waypoint UX) — mostly manual QA.
    Race conditions between UI event loop and simulator real-time clock scheduling (some can be covered by careful unit tests but full concurrency in browser environment needs manual/E2E).
    Cross-origin caching/edge cases for remote project/binary fetch (network conditions variability).
    Accessibility checks require manual review and screen reader testing.
    Performance on extremely large circuits in real user hardware — measurable but not deterministic across environments.

Important decision points / open questions / potential conflicts (must resolve before coding)

    RAM word width and endianness:
        Required: define RAM word width (8-bit? configurable?). Also define mapping of binary file bytes to addresses (endianness). If RAM addr pins count defines depth, how to handle file larger than depth*wordWidth — truncate vs error.
    Tristate/net semantics:
        When multiple drivers present: if multiple actively drive conflicting values (0 vs 1), treat as error. If only Z drivers, define net read value (undefined) — proposal: read as 0 by default but warn. Confirm desired behavior.
    Wire driver definition:
        Wires are bidirectional structural nets; but primitives have pins classified as input/output/tristate. Ensure simulator treats outputs as drivers and inputs as readers. Confirm acceptability of multi-driver nets (multiple active outputs) -> treat as error.
    Clock scheduling and simulation time model:
        Simulator is edge-mapped; clocks produce edge events based on real time or simulated ticks? Proposal: clock schedules events by wall-clock using requestAnimationFrame/timeouts for UI mode, but allow deterministic step mode (for tests) using stepSimulation(dt). Confirm.
    NAND output change counter semantics:
        Set a maximum changes threshold per propagation session before declaring loop (e.g., 1000 changes). Decide threshold and whether counter persists across runs or per-event propagation.
    Chip editing model:
        Two options:
            Modal editing (drop into chip and return) — simple.
            Tabbed editors with independent workspaces and save-on-demand — more flexible.
        You asked for a recommendation: tabbed editing with explicit save gives less accidental overwrite and easier multi-chip edits; but is slightly more complex. Confirm choice.
    Copy/paste semantics:
        If selection includes chips and primitives, internal wires preserved. For pasted chips, must generate new instance ids. Confirm whether pasted chips keep references to external chips or copy them.
    Project import id collisions:
        When importing, if chip IDs collide with local, resolve by renaming imported ids and remapping references. Confirm auto-rename policy.
    Logic table synthesis mapping to custom chips:
        How to determine a match: exact boolean function match with same input/output pin ordering? Confirm tolerant matching (e.g., permutations) or strict.
    Error reporting & UI behavior:
        Format for showing simulation warnings/errors (modal, console panel, per-primitive markers).

